    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "RFF implementation creates a fast approximation of the RBF kernel by sampling random weights and phases, then mapping each input through a cosine function. It computes \n",
        "𝑋𝑊+𝑏\n",
        " (supporting both dense and sparse data) and outputs sqrt(2/𝐷)cos⁡(⋅), giving a \n",
        "𝐷\n",
        "-dimensional feature vector that lets linear models behave like nonlinear ones."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RU6pCUOmHhBJ"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Observations on Learning Rate:**\n",
        "A learning rate of 0.1 caused unstable updates for SGD and Momentum on some datasets.\n",
        "A learning rate of 0.001 converged too slowly.\n",
        "Adagrad handled larger learning rates well because it adapts the step size for each parameter automatically."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3iO2WBeLH5I2"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Observation on Batch size:**\n",
        "Small batch sizes produced noisier gradients but sometimes converged faster initially.\n",
        "Larger batch sizes gave smoother convergence and significantly reduced runtime on large datasets.\n",
        "For Higgs, small batch sizes were computationally expensive, so only large batches were feasible.\n",
        "IMDB benefited from larger batches because of its sparse high-dimensional representation."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "T5i07gsQIVka"
      },
      "source": [
        "SGD and Momentum required carefully tuned learning rates and decaying schedules.\n",
        "Adagrad was less sensitive to learning rate tuning because of its adaptive updates and therefore used a larger constant learning rate.\n",
        "\n",
        "Overall, optimizer-specific and dataset-specific tuning significantly improved convergence speed and final performance."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "pUtE0njgJinq"
      },
      "source": [
        "Implementation:\n",
        "\n",
        "Gradients were computed using active hinge-loss examples (samples with margin <1).\n",
        "L\n",
        "2\n",
        "\t​\n",
        "\n",
        " regularization was added to the gradient.\n",
        "A decaying learning-rate schedule was used to improve convergence stability.\n",
        "\n",
        "SGD is simple and computationally efficient but can produce noisy updates.\n",
        "\n",
        "Momentum SGD accelerates SGD by maintaining a running velocity vector that accumulates previous gradients.\n",
        "\n",
        "The velocity vector was initialized to zero.\n",
        "A decaying learning-rate schedule was also used.\n",
        "\n",
        "Momentum reduced oscillations and generally converged faster than plain SGD."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "sLnuW3Q2KAXw"
      },
      "source": [
        "Adagrad adapts the learning rate individually for each parameter based on the history of squared gradients.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\t​\n"
      ]
    },
